title: For Sale:   Correct WWII Winchester M1 Carbine c. early 1944
postcontent: As war approached in the late 1930s, the Army's Infantry branch began to see the need for a lightweight carbine that could replace the Model 1911 pistol and the Thompson M1928 Submachine Gun. Initially, the Ordnance Department was not receptive to the idea stating that the newly-adopted M1 Garand service rifle was adequate as a long-arm for all purposes and that the 1911A1 Service Pistol had a fine service record and was indispensable for staff officers and NCOs, crew served weapons team members, medics, etc. But the Army's Chief of Infantry was insistent and when funds became available in mid-1940, the Ordnance Department was finally directed to produce a prototype firearm that did not weigh in excess of 5 pounds with an effective range up to 300 yards.

title: For Sale:  1952 Polish M44 Mosin Nagant
postcontent: I had it appraised today, 7/12, by a local gun store in order to get a better idea of its condition, worth, etc.  I'll detail below what I learned.A. There is an embargo on these rifles, with people demanding higher prices for the M44 in particular.  What is in circulation is it, with no more expected anytime soon.  B. The owner said he'd place a price of $350.00 on the rifle, and considered it to be a fine example of the Mosin Nagant.  He wouldn't mind buying it for his own collection.C. The rifle has been refinished, but the job was done well.  The bolt and buttplate are painted camo green, but doesn't affect functionality or worth by any means due to it being easily removed by whoever wishes to do so.D. The bore is good, with no signs of being re-bored or counter-bored.Overall, the gun is a good military, Cold War era collectible with a relatively cheap price attached to it.  The ammo is also easily, and cheaply, found.  I've owned it for twelve years now, and I will attest that it is probably the most interesting gun I've ever shot in regards to bolt actions, especially if done at dusk.  It kicks like a mule, but that, to me, is just part of its rough character.  Make no mistake, it's a peasants weapon.  It is considered a SHTF necessity by some.  And, if you're a fan of the Walking Dead, the same model can be seen being carried by Maggie.  Personally, if I can't sell it, I'll just frame it, put an image of Maggie carrying one, then sell it for a couple hundred more to an avid Walking Dead fan.  That is not likely to happen, but not a terrible idea.
